UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 279
1 AN ACT relating to motor vehicle titles.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 Section 1. KRS 186A.295 is amended to read as follows:
4 (1) (a) Subject to the limitations in paragraph (c) of this subsection, any person or
5 entity having a motor vehicle or trailer that has been destroyed, to the extent
6 that its repair cannot be obtained through usual commercial repair services, at
7 a cost less than its retail value as prescribed by a nationally accepted used car
8 valuation guide or tool identified under KRS 304.20-110, or from which two
9 (2) or more parts which typically bear a vehicle identification number placed
10 thereon by the manufacturer have been removed, or which he or she removes,
11 shall surrender the certificate of title for the vehicle for which he or she has a
12 certificate of title in his, or her, or another name, to the county clerk of the
13 county in which the vehicle is located. The clerk shall immediately forward
14 the surrendered title to Frankfort with instructions for canceling the title.
15 (b) Any person or entity engaged in the sale of used motor vehicle or trailer parts,
16 or the recycling or salvage of them, shall surrender the certificate of title for
17 any vehicle in his or her possession, and for which he or she has a certificate
18 of title, whether in his or her or another name, if the vehicle is destroyed
19 within the meaning of paragraph (a) of this subsection, or from which two (2)
20 or more parts which typically bear a vehicle identification number placed
21 thereon by a manufacturer have been removed, or which he or she removes, to
22 the county clerk of the county in which the vehicle is located. The clerk shall
23 immediately forward the surrendered title to Frankfort with instructions for
24 canceling the title.
25 (c) The calculation of the cost of repair referenced in paragraph (a) of this
26 subsection shall not include the cost of parts and labor to make cosmetic
27 repairs to a motor vehicle or trailer that affect the vehicle's appearance
Page 1 of 12
XXXX 12/12/2025 2:48 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 279
1 without impact to the safety, structural integrity, or drivability of the motor
2 vehicle or trailer.
3 (d) The surrender of the certificate of title pursuant to this section shall be made
4 within ten (10) working days, next succeeding the day when the vehicle was
5 received, destroyed, or next succeeding the day during which a second part
6 was removed.
7 (2) Each county clerk shall receive without charge, a certificate surrendered in
8 accordance with this section, cancel it, and remit it to the Department of Vehicle
9 Regulation, and take any other action related to it, as required by the Department of
10 Vehicle Regulation.
11 (3) If the calculation of the cost of repair in subsection (1)(c) of this section exempts
12 a vehicle from having the certificate of title surrendered, the title shall be branded
13 as a salvage title in accordance with Section 2 of this Act.
14 Section 2. KRS 186A.520 is amended to read as follows:
15 (1) Except as provided in KRS 186A.555, a salvage title shall be obtained by the owner
16 of a motor vehicle that meets the following definition of a salvage vehicle:
17 (a) 1. A vehicle that[which] has been wrecked, destroyed, or damaged, to the
18 extent that the total estimated or actual cost of parts and labor to rebuild
19 or reconstruct the vehicle to its preaccident condition and for legal
20 operation on the roads or highways, not including the cost of parts and
21 labor to reinstall a deployed airbag system, exceeds seventy-five percent
22 (75%) of the retail value of the vehicle, as prescribed by a nationally
23 accepted used car valuation guide or tool identified under KRS 304.20-
24 110.
25 2.[(b)] The value of repair parts for purposes of this
26 paragraph[definition] shall be determined by using the current
27 published retail cost of the parts equal in kind and quality to the parts to
Page 2 of 12
XXXX 12/12/2025 2:48 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 279
1 be replaced or the actual retail cost of the repair parts used in repair.
2 3.[(c)] The labor costs of repairs for purposes of this paragraph[section]
3 shall be computed by using the hourly labor rate and time allocations
4 which are reasonable and customary in the automobile repair industry in
5 the community where the repairs are performed.
6 4.[(d)] Airbag reinstallation costs which are excluded from the seventy-
7 five percent (75%) computation as set forth in subparagraph
8 1.[paragraph (a)] of this paragraph[subsection] shall be included by an
9 insurer in the computation of the total physical damage estimate
10 according to the terms and conditions of individual policies, provided
11 that the total costs payable by an insurer do not exceed the total retail
12 value of the vehicle; or
13 (b) A vehicle that is exempt from certificate of title surrender under subsection
14 (3) of Section 1 of this Act.
15 (2) The owner or an authorized agent of a motor vehicle that meets the definition of a
16 salvage vehicle as set forth in subsection (1) of this section shall, within fifteen (15)
17 days from the receipt of all necessary paperwork required by this chapter, submit an
18 application to the county clerk, on a form prescribed by the Department of Vehicle
19 Regulation, for a salvage title, accompanied by a properly endorsed certificate of
20 title and any lien satisfactions, if any appear, as may be required.
21 (3) The county clerk shall retain a copy of each salvage title application received and
22 shall forward the original and its supporting documents to the Department of
23 Vehicle Regulation in a manner similar to that for handling of an application for a
24 title.
25 (4) The county clerk shall rely on the information provided by the owner or authorized
26 agent, including a county of residence designation, on:
27 (a) Any approved, notarized state form utilized in lien titling or the title transfer
Page 3 of 12
XXXX 12/12/2025 2:48 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 279
1 process signed by the owner or authorized agent; and
2 (b) Any document submitted during the transfer of a salvage vehicle from an
3 owner to an insurer.
4 Reliance on the foregoing by the county clerk shall relieve the office of the county
5 clerk from liability to any third party claiming failure to comply with this section.
6 (5) The Department of Vehicle Regulation shall process the salvage title application in
7 a manner similar to that used in processing a title application and the salvage title
8 shall be delivered in a like manner of a title. Salvage titles shall be construed as
9 proof of ownership of a vehicle in a state as to be unusable upon the highways of
10 the Commonwealth.
11 (6) A vehicle shall not be issued a registration for highway use as long as a salvage title
12 is in force. The only time a vehicle with a salvage title may be operated upon the
13 highways of the Commonwealth is when it is in route to or from an inspection by
14 the certified inspector prior to obtaining a certificate of title after having been
15 rebuilt as per KRS 186.115.
16 (7) Notwithstanding the provisions of KRS 369.103, when a salvage vehicle is
17 transferred from an owner to an insurer, the following shall be exempted from the
18 requirements of notarization, including exemption from the notarization of
19 electronic signature requirements of KRS Chapter 423:
20 (a) The transfer of ownership on the certificate of title;
21 (b) Any power of attorney required in connection with the transfer of ownership
22 to the insurer;
23 (c) Any required odometer disclosure statement;
24 (d) The application for a salvage certificate of title; and
25 (e) The transfer of ownership on the salvage certificate of title issued.
26 (8) Subsections (2) to (5) of this section shall not apply to applications for salvage title
27 using the electronic title application and registration system established under KRS
